  "text": "Conventionally the pathogen was characterized by its host range and divided into five races. race 1 infect solanaceae family and many other hosts; race 2 infect primarily banana; race 3 infect potato, tomato and a few other hosts, usually in more temperate conditions; race 4 infect ginger and race 5 infect mulberry [CITATION_1] . In past few decades another classification was adapted; R. solanacearum was classified into six biovars along with the race. Biovars classification is based on the ability to produce acid from carbohydrates. The only association between races and biovars is that race 3 corresponds to biovar 2 [CITATION_2] . These methods of characterization are of limited utility because, the host range overlaps especially after artificial inoculation (Santana et al., 2012) .",
